## Task

1. Write a specific, descriptive essay title in {{ language }}. If the brief topic is generic (e.g. "for a specific X"), use the clarifications to produce a concrete title. The title must reflect the actual subject of the essay, not repeat the assignment description.
2. Identify the core question or topic the essay must address.
3. Formulate a clear thesis statement (1-2 sentences) in {{ language }}.
4. Break the essay into sections.
5. Allocate word counts per section summing to the overall target.
6. Write 6-8 targeted search queries for finding academic sources (in both Greek and English).

## Structure Preservation ŌĆö CRITICAL

- If the assignment brief contains an explicit user-provided structure, outline, list of headings, required section names, required order, or required subsection count, you MUST preserve it in the plan.
- Treat explicit structure requirements as binding unless they are internally contradictory or impossible to map to a coherent essay.
- Do NOT replace a user-provided structure with a standard template just because a generic academic structure would be more typical.
- Do NOT collapse, merge, rename, reorder, or invent major sections when the user already specified them.
- If exact headings were provided, preserve their meaning and wording as closely as possible. Only make minimal normalization needed for language consistency or formatting.
- Use a default essay structure only when the brief does not provide one.

## Content Outline Detail

Each section's `content_outline` should be detailed enough for independent writing:
- What arguments/sub-topics to develop
- Which types of evidence/data to present
- How the section relates to the thesis
- Any specific examples or case studies to include

Each section object must also include `requires_full_context`:
- Set it to `true` for introduction, conclusion, synthesis, epilogue, methodology wrap-up, or any section whose quality depends on seeing the rest of the drafted essay.
- Set it to `false` for most regular body sections that can be drafted independently.

## Word Allocation Guidelines

| Essay Length | Introduction | Per Body Section | Conclusion |
|---|---|---|---|
| < 2000 words | 10-12% | Divide remaining equally | 10-12% |
| 2000-4000 words | 10-15% | Divide remaining by importance | 10-15% |
| > 4000 words | 8-10% | Divide remaining by importance | 8-10% |

